article.headline: Hawaii 92, New Orleans 64
article.story: HONOLULU (AP) -- Michael Kuebler scored 29 points, including 17 in the second half, as Hawaii won its fourth straight game by defeating New Orleans 92-64 Saturday night in the Adidas Festival. Kuebler was 9-of-18 from the field and converted all six of his free-throw attempts. The senior's 29 points tied his career-high performance against Chaminade on Nov. 25. But he preferred to talk about his teammates' play after the game. Kuebler said the team is finally gelling as a unit. "A lot of it is the guys knowing their role and where to be on the court," he said. "We're finally getting that game-type situations that you can't get in practice." Hawaii coach Riley Wallace agrees. "That's what we've been preaching, team play," he said. "And this team is really coming together." Phil Martin had 18 points and Julian Sensley had his breakout game with 16 points, 10 rebounds and seven assists for Hawaii (5-2). "The last couple games, I wasn't really confident in my shot, so I was kind of holding back," Sensley said. "I kind of was letting them fly tonight, fortunately some dropped." Haim Shimonovich also had a double-double with 13 points and 10 boards. "I think the biggest key is that Haim's gotten in shape," Wallace said. "He played the whole 20 minutes in the first half. By him being in shape, getting up and down the floor, the team is pushing a little more too, and we're going to score more points that way." Hawaii, which never trailed after taking a 10-9 lead, ran away in the second half, closing the game with a 17-4 run. Martin's one-handed putback capped a 13-4 run in the first half that expanded Hawaii's lead to 32-20. The Rainbow Warriors went on an 8-2 run to take a 43-30 lead at the break. The Rainbow Warriors shot 54 percent from the field, compared with 36 percent for the Privateers. Hawaii also out-rebounded New Orleans 43-33. New Orleans (4-3) was led by Ben Elias' 16 points and Johnell Smith's 15 points. The Privateers were dismal from beyond the arc, hitting just 3-of-20 of their 3-point shots. Hawaii outscored its opponents by an average of 29 points in the two-day Adidas Festival. "All the hard work we've been putting in and the time off just prepared us mentally and physically for the game," said Martin, who became the 11th player in school history to break the 1,000-career point mark. "Each game you can see us getting better and better." In the early matchup Saturday, Texas Southern defeated Idaho State 73-63.
